flowRoot.flowPara: Response Signatures outperform Pathway Methods for Drug Associations

A. Volcano plot of pan-cancer associations between drug response (IC50) and inferred pathway score using our method (left) and GSEA for corresponding pathways using Gene Ontology (upper right) and Reactome (lower right). Effect size on the x-axis, FDR-adjusted p-values on y. Circle size corresponds to numre of data points, empty circles drop out of significance if conditioned.
B. Volcano plot of cancer-specific associations. Legend as in panel A.
C. Examples of linear fits for tissue-specific association using our method. Headings refer to cancer type, drug, and pathway. Horizontal axis shows inferred pathway score, vertical axis log(IC50).
D. Examples of two instances where a mutation marker is known for a given association, but our pathway scores can improve upon its association.
Pan-cancer associations are dominated by MAPK activation and related inhibitors.
How to show, for the general case, that pathway scores improve on mutations?
MAPK and p53 scores drive drug response across all cancer types

A. Pan-cancer associations of cell lines in the GDSC panel and drug response. Volcano plot on left, where an effect size of smaller than zero indicates sensitivity markers (shown in green) and greater than zero resistance markers (shown in red); contribution of tissues regressed out; P-values FDR-adjusted. Overview of the MAPK pathway and its inhibitors on the right. Our method shows strong associations between activity of the MAPK pathway and its inhibitors as well as the known Nutlin-3a:TP53 interaction, which implies that MAPK/EGFR and p53 signaling are important in driving drug response across all cancers.

B. Comparison of the associations obtained by different pathway methods. Number of associations (log) on the vertical axis, - log FDR on the horizontal axis. Our method yields more and stronger associations compared to all other pathway methods, and driver mutations only yield more for TP53 and drugs that were specifically designed to bind to a mutated protein. PARADIGM not shown because no associations < 10% FDR.

C. Improvement of stratification when using pathway markers in addition to mutations. The drug IC50 to Trametinib (top left), AZ628 (bottom left), Dabrafenib (top right) and Nutlin-3a (bottom right) are shown on the vertical axis, different subsets on the horizontal: all is across all tissues, wt/gene name indicates mutation status of this set of genes. MAPK/p53 on the right is stratification by pathway score alone. The more sensitive phenotype is further stratified by pathway scores where the color indicates activity, including fold changes of the median and p-values for this stratification.
